          "body": "Three times the itinerary's repetitive formula breaks — and each interruption is theologically significant. At 33:8, the crossing of the sea is noted without fanfare: 'they passed through the midst of the sea into the wilderness.' The event that defines Israel's entire self-understanding in later Scripture (Psalm 106, Isaiah 43, 1 Corinthians 10) is given one clause in the march-list. The restraint is not indifference but proportion: in the grand map of Israel's journey, even the Sea crossing was one station among many, each equally under God's hand. At 33:38-39, Aaron's death is given four verses — the most sustained interruption in the chapter. He was 123 years old; he died at the command of the LORD; the date is precise to the day. The particularity of his death forces the reader to reckon with the generation that refused to enter: their priestly representative died outside the land. At 33:40, the Canaanite king of Arad noted that Israel was coming — an intelligence report that tells the reader the nations are already afraid. The enemies of God's people are paying attention."
